<li id="cite_note-97"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-97">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation Journal">Roberts, James. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/hipgnotic-suggestion/"><i>Hipgnotic Suggestion</i></a>. <i><a href="Frieze_(magazine)" title="Frieze (magazine)">Frieze</a></i><span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/hipgnotic-suggestion/">http://www.frieze.com/issue/article/hipgnotic-suggestion/</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 12 September 2012</span>. "Throughout the 70s many of the more successful rock bands adopted similarly abstract imagery, in particular Led Zeppelin (the album IV, 1971, dispensed with their name and the title of the record entirely) and Pink Floyd, who, following the Beatles, were only the second band to be allowed by EMI to use an outside designer."</span></span></li>
